    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Trie Explanation</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            margin: 20px;\n        }\n        .text-explanation {\n            font-size: 18px;\n            margin-bottom: 10px;\n        }\n        .button {\n            margin-top: 10px;\n            padding: 5px 10px;\n            border: none;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            background-color: #4CAF50;\n            color: #fff;\n            cursor: pointer;\n        }\n        .button:hover {\n            background-color: #3e8e41;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>Trie Explanation</h1>\n    <p id=\"text-explanation\"></p>\n    <p id=\"algorithm-explanation\"></p>\n    <p id=\"algorithm-description\"></p>\n    <p id=\"example\"></p>\n    <button id=\"demo-button\">Run Demo</button>\n    <script>\n        const textExplanation = document.getElementById('text-explanation');\n        const algorithmExplanation = document.getElementById('algorithm-explanation');\n        const algorithmDescription = document.getElementById('algorithm-description');\n        const demoButton = document.getElementById('demo-button');\n\n        const textExample = `\n            The Trie data structure is a tree-like data structure in which each node stores a string. It is used to store and retrieve strings efficiently.\n\n            Here is how it works:\n            - Each node in the Trie has a unique key (a string) and a set of child nodes (also strings).\n            - When a string is inserted into the Trie, it is split into its constituent parts (or \"leaves\").\n            - Each leaf node is then inserted into the Trie, creating a new path for the string.\n\n            The Trie has several key benefits:\n            - It allows for fast lookup of strings, with an average time complexity of O(m), where m is the length of the string.\n            - It allows for efficient insertion and deletion of strings, with an average time complexity of O(m).\n            - It can be used to store strings of varying lengths, with a maximum length of m.\n        `;\n\n        const algorithm = `\n            Here is an example of how to implement a Trie in JavaScript:\n\n            ```javascript\n            class Trie {\n                constructor() {\n                    this.root = {};\n                }\n\n                insert(word) {\n                    let node = this.root;\n                    for (let char of word) {\n                        if (!node[char]) {\n                            node[char] = {};\n                        }\n                        node = node[char];\n                    }\n                    node.isWord = true;\n                }\n\n                search(word) {\n                    let node = this.root;\n                    for (let char of word) {\n                        if (!node[char]) {\n                            return false;\n                        }\n                        node = node[char];\n                    }\n                    return node.isWord;\n                }\n\n                startsWith(prefix) {\n                    let node = this.root;\n                    for (let char of prefix) {\n                        if (!node[char]) {\n                            return false;\n                        }\n                        node = node[char];\n                    }\n                    return true;\n                }\n            }\n            ```\n\n            To use the Trie, create a new instance and call the `insert` method to add words to the Trie, the `search` method to check if a word exists, and the `startsWith` method to check if a prefix exists.\n        ``;\n\n        const algorithmDescription = `\n            A Trie (also known as a prefix tree) is a tree-like data structure in which each node stores a string. It is used to store and retrieve strings efficiently.\n\n            The Trie is a powerful data structure with several key benefits:\n            - It allows for fast lookup of strings, with an average time complexity of O(m), where m is the length of the string.\n            - It allows for efficient insertion and deletion of strings, with an average time complexity of O(m).\n            - It can be used to store strings of varying lengths, with a maximum length of m.\n        `;\n\n        textExplanation.textContent = textExample;\n        algorithmExplanation.textContent = algorithm;\n        algorithmDescription.textContent = algorithmDescription;\n\n        demoButton.addEventListener('click', () => {\n            console.log('Demo button clicked!');\n        });\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
